17 (9)(8) 'Massage therapy' or 'massage' means the application of a system of structured
18 touch, pressure, movement, and holding to the soft tissue of the body in which the
19 primary intent is to enhance or restore health and well-being. Such term includes
20 complementary methods, including without limitation cupping therapy, taping
21 techniques, the external application of water, superficial heat, superficial cold, lubricants,
22 salt scrubs, or other topical preparations and the use of commercially available
23 electromechanical devices which do not require the use of transcutaneous electrodes and
24 which mimic or enhance the actions possible by the hands; the term also includes
25 determining whether massage therapy is appropriate or contraindicated, or whether
26 referral to another health care provider is appropriate. Such term shall not include the use
27 of ultrasound, fluidotherapy, laser, and other methods of deep thermal modalities.
28 (10)(9) 'Massage therapy business' means an entity where the practice of or engagement
29 in massage therapy is performed by a licensed massage therapist.
30 (11)(10) 'Person' means a natural person only.
31 (12)(11) 'Provisionally permitted massage therapist' means a person issued a provisional
32 permit under this chapter."
33 SECTION 2.
34 Said article is further amended by adding a new subsection to Code Section 43-24A-15,
35 relating to unlawful acts, to read as follows:
36 "(g) Beginning on August 1, 2025, it shall be a violation of this chapter for any person or
37 entity to open for business or otherwise operate a massage therapy business between
38 10:00 P.M. and 6:00 A.M."
39 SECTION 3.
40 All laws and parts of laws in conflict with this Act are repealed.
